The brightness of celestial bodies is indicated by the apparent magnitude and absolute magnitude; Apparent magnitude: The magnitude number shown on a star chart reflects the brightness we see from stars, with smaller numbers indicating brighter stars. This magnitude number does not reflect the actual luminosity of the star itself, as it does not consider the distance of the star (a star with the same luminosity appears less bright to us when it is farther away), so we refer to this magnitude number as the apparent magnitude. Based on prolonged observation, the faintest stars visible to the naked eye are sixth-magnitude stars. From first to sixth magnitude, each step represents a difference of five magnitudes, and there is a 100-fold difference in brightness. Two stars that differ by one magnitude have a brightness difference of 2.512 times; the Sun's magnitude is set at -26.7, and the full moon has an approximate magnitude of -12.6. Generally, stars fainter than sixth magnitude require a telescope for observation; Absolute magnitude: This measures the brightness of a celestial body if it were moved to a distance of 10 parsecs (32.6 light-years) from Earth. It reflects the actual luminosity of the celestial body;
Saturn is a planet with a variable brightness between 0.8 and 1.2 magnitudes. Currently located in Virgo, it can be observed in the eastern sky before dawn, slightly brighter than Regulus, hence option A is incorrect; Polaris, also known as α UMi, has a magnitude of 2.02, making it the 50th brightest star in the sky (various star charts may show slight differences). Clearly, after comparison, it can be concluded that among these four stars, Polaris—α UMi is the faintest, hence option B is correct;
Arcturus, α Bootis, with a magnitude of 0.04, is the fifth brightest star in the sky, therefore option C is incorrect; Altair, or β Aquilae, with a magnitude of 0.76, is the twelfth brightest star in the sky, hence option D is incorrect;
Therefore, the correct choice is: B
